Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law requires a person to provide certain documentation which is current and
2 valid for purposes of certain provisions relating to elections. (See e.g., NRS 293.269915,
3 293.2725, 293.507, 293.5742, 293.57688, 293.5837, 293.5842, 293.5847, 293C.26314)
4 Section 1.4 of this bill defines the term “current and valid” for such purposes and section 1.7
5 of this bill makes that definition applicable to certain provisions relating to elections.
6 Existing law sets forth provisions governing the preparation, distribution and casting of
7 mail ballots and requires a county or city clerk, as applicable, to prepare and distribute to each
8 active registered voter in the county or city and certain other persons who register to vote a
9 mail ballot for every election. (NRS 293.269911-293.269937, 293C.263-293C.26337)
10 Sections 1.6, 11.3, 28.3 and 32.3 of this bill authorize an active registered voter who is
11 eligible to receive a mail ballot to submit a request to the county or city clerk, as applicable, to
12 receive a mail ballot if he or she is unable to access his or her mail ballot or appear in person
13 at the polls due to an emergency. Sections 1.6 and 28.3 further require a county or city clerk
14 to distribute a mail ballot to such a voter after verifying the voter’s eligibility and that he or
15 she has not already voted. Sections 1.9, 11.5, 28.7 and 32.7 of this bill make certain
16 provisions relating to mail ballots, including the definition of “mail ballot” and provisions
17 concerning the marking and signing the mail ballot of another voter, applicable to ballots
18 requested pursuant to sections 1.6 and 28.3.
19 Section 2 of this bill removes the prohibition for a person to be a candidate of a major
20 political party for partisan office if the person has changed certain information on an
21 application to register to vote in a state other than this State during the time beginning on
22 December 31 preceding the closing filing date for an election and ending on the date of the
23 election. (NRS 293.176)
24 Existing law requires an independent candidate for partisan office to file a declaration of
25 candidacy. (NRS 293.200) Existing law further sets forth the form for a declaration of
26 candidacy for all candidates for partisan office. (NRS 293.177) Section 3 of this bill sets forth
27 the form for the declaration of candidacy for an independent candidate for partisan office.
28 Section 5 of this bill makes conforming changes to clarify that the declaration of candidacy
29 for an independent candidate must be in the form set forth in section 3.
30 Existing law sets forth certain fees for filing a declaration of candidacy and provides that
31 the fee for filing a declaration of candidacy may be paid by cash, cashier’s check or certified
32 check. (NRS 293.193) Section 4 of this bill: (1) provides that such a fee may also be paid by
33 credit card if the filing officer accepts such a method of payment; (2) revises the description of
34 certain offices; and (3) reorganizes existing fees set forth in other provisions of existing law in
35 to this schedule of fees.
36 Existing law requires a county clerk, immediately upon receipt of the certified list of
37 candidates for judicial and nonjudicial office, to publish a notice of primary election or
38 general election in a newspaper of general circulation in the county once a week for 2
39 successive weeks and requires such notice to contain: (1) the date of the election; (2) the
40 location of the polling places; and (3) the hours during which the polling places will be open
41 for voting. (NRS 293.203) Section 6 of this bill requires such notice to additionally contain:
42 (1) the names of the candidates; and (2) the office for which each candidate is running and, if
43 the office is partisan, the party under which the candidate is running. Section 39 of this bill
44 similarly requires the names of the qualified candidates who will be on the ballot at the
45 presidential preference primary election and the major political party with which each
46 candidate is affiliated to be included on such notice for a presidential preference primary
47 election. (NRS 298.670)
48 Existing law authorizes a county clerk to appoint a pupil as a trainee for the position of
49 election board officer and sets forth the qualifications for such an appointment, including a
50 requirement that the pupil is appointed without party affiliation. (NRS 293.2175, 293C.222)
51 Sections 7 and 31 of this bill clarify that a pupil may be appointed as a trainee regardless of
52 his or her affiliation with a political party, including any designation of party affiliation on the
53 pupil’s application to preregister or register to vote.
54 Existing law requires the Secretary of State to develop and provide a training course to
55 each county clerk and city clerk related to elections procedures and requires the Secretary of

