125 Existing federal law sets forth certain requirements for the removal of a voter from the
126 official list of eligible voters which prohibit a state from removing the name of a registered
127 voter unless the voter: (1) confirms a change of residence outside of the registrar’s jurisdiction
128 in writing; or (2) fails to respond to a notice sent to his or her residence and has not voted or
129 appeared to vote for a period of time after a notice has been mailed to his or her residence. (52
130 U.S.C. § 20507) Sections 20 and 21 of this bill require a county clerk to mail a notice and
131 conduct any correction or removal of a registered voter in accordance with existing federal
132 law.
133 Sections 20 and 23.5 of this bill provide that certain notifications that a county clerk is
134 required to mail to the current residence of a person are required instead to be mailed to the
135 current mailing address of the person. (NRS 293.530, 293.57693)
136 Existing law: (1) authorizes a voter to update his or her voter registration information
137 after the close of registration for an election; and (2) requires the county or city clerk to
138 authorize a voter to update his or her voter registration information by the use of a paper
139 application or the computer system established by the Secretary of State. (NRS 293.5832)
140 Section 24 of this bill authorizes the county or city clerk to also authorize an additional
141 method for updating such voter registration information at a polling place during early voting
142 by personal appearance and on election day. Section 24 further: (1) requires the county or city
143 clerk to send a mail ballot to such a voter if the voter updates the information 14 or more days
144 before the election; and (2) provides that a voter who updates information less than 14 days
145 before the election may vote only in person in that election only at a polling place. Finally,
146 section 24 clarifies that all other provisions of law relating to voting in person or by mail still
147 apply to a registered voter who updates his or her voter registration information after the close
148 of voter registration for the election.
149 Existing law prohibits a person from electioneering during the time a polling place for
150 early voting is open for voting in or within 100 feet from the entrance to the voting area. (NRS
151 293.361) Section 11.7 of this bill instead prohibits such actions within 100 feet of the entrance
152 to a building, other structure or jail in which a polling place is located.
153 Existing law prohibits a person from voting more than once at the same election. (NRS
154 293.780) Section 48 of this bill repeals existing law that prohibits a person from being
155 preregistered or registered to vote in more than one county at a time. (NRS 293.810) Section
156 24.7 of this bill provides that a person votes more than once at the same election if he or she
157 votes: (1) more than once in certain elections in this State; or (2) in the same primary or
158 general election in this State and at least one other state.
159 Existing law requires a county or city clerk or other election official to immediately
160 notify the Secretary of State if the clerk or official identifies or is informed of a confirmed
161 attack or attempted attack on the security of an information system used by the clerk or
162 official. (NRS 293.875) Section 26 of this bill requires the Secretary of State to adopt by
163 regulation a cyber-incident response plan for elections. Section 26 also requires a county or
164 city clerk or other election official to notify the Secretary of State, the Governor and the
165 Legislative Commission of any cyber-incident or attempted cyber-incident on the security of
166 an information system used by the county or city clerk or other election official in accordance
167 with the cyber-incident response plan.
168 Existing law authorizes certain persons, including a spouse, domestic partner or minor
169 child of such a person, to request that personal information contained in the records of the
170 Secretary of State, a county or city clerk, a county recorder or a county assessor be kept
171 confidential. (NRS 247.540, 250.140, 293.908) Sections 27, 40 and 41 of this bill
172 additionally authorize the elderly parent of such a person to request that such information be
173 kept confidential.

